                      <h1 class="title">Drupal Usability : Looking at the Drupal UI from a Subject Oriented Perspective</h1>
                                                  <div class="node node-type-session" id="node-105"><div class="node-inner">

  
  
  <div class="picture"><a href="michael-baynger" title="View user profile."><img src="../sites/2008.drupalcamptoronto.org/files/pictures/picture-51.jpg" alt="useradvocate&#039;s picture" title="useradvocate&#039;s picture"  /></a></div>
      <div class="submitted">
      Submitted by <a href="michael-baynger" title="View user profile.">useradvocate</a> on May 7, 2008 - 9:36pm.    </div>
  
  
  <div class="content">
    <p>Subject Oriented Design is a much needed and logical follow up to Object Oriented Design â€“ but what is it and how can it help with improving the usability of Drupal's administration interface? To <em>begin</em> to answer these questions Iâ€™m proposing a session with these goals:<br />
â€¢	To explore some of the meaning and importance of subject oriented design.<br />
â€¢	To encourage Drupal designers and developers to look at their work from a subject oriented perspective.<br />
â€¢	To share some practical hints as to how to go about this. (Given that it's an endless journey we can only take a few steps in one session.)<br />
â€¢	To loosen some of the right bolts in the Drupal UX paradigm while still keeping the architectural pivot points in tact.<br />
â€¢	To help me, as a usability expert and Drupal newcomer, understand more about what matters to you, as developers, designers and users of Drupal.<br />
â€¢	To establish that Salsa dancing is the best benchmark around for evaluating user experiences.</p>
<p>A little bit about me. I am a usability expert who also has spent a couple of decades designing and building commercial software. Originally from a Fine Arts background, I am passionate about the user experience and I see Drupal Theming as fertile ground for accomplishing significant usability improvements to online experiences. </p>
<p>Given that, Iâ€™ve spent the last two months introducing myself to Drupal by coming in the back door of learning the phptemplate system. Iâ€™m still quite able to become bewildered by the administration interface and thatâ€™s a pretty valuable place to be from a usability testing point of view â€“ no assumptions about how it works!  I invite you to â€˜share my painâ€™ and hear some of what I can bring from my experience as a user interface systems architect and to share your own perspectives on this hot topic. </p>
<p>For more about my past lives please check out  my <a href='http://www.mbaynger.com' target='_blank'>'web resume' site</a></p>
